post_text:
SCHOOL CLOSURE ALERT:
Dear Students and Families - due to continued poor air quality due to smoke from the wildfires, ALL SOUTH UMPQUA SCHOOLS WILL BE CLOSED TUESDAY SEPTEMBER 15th, and there will be no meal delivery service available. This closure includes in-person and distance learning.

Please know that we are anxious to have students back in their classes, and will continue to monitor the air quality situation and provide updates. An all-call will go out to families this afternoon.

Staff will receive notifications from their supervisors.
Thank you.

post_text: HUGE thanks to our amazing local fire departments! It looks like we had a hot spot in an electrical panel that triggered a fire alarm at the high school this morning. Tri City, Canyonville, Myrtle Creek, and Riddle fire crews all responded so quickly! Fortunately there was smoke, but no flames!

post_text: Dear Students and Families -- It is with heavy hearts that we announce changes to our district reopening plans. Following the new metrics and requirements for reopening schools, we will begin our school year offering in-person instruction for students in grades K-3, and Comprehensive Distance Learning for students in grades 4-12. We are hopeful our county will meet the required metrics and that we will be able to resume our plans for in-person learning K-12, with options for students and families who prefer or require distance learning. The attached letter (also posted on the district website) includes more detail, and your child's school will also be sending specific information out soon.

"Thank a Teacher/School Worker"

Here’s an opportunity to show your appreciation and celebrate the dedication to students and their education.

Please click on the link in the Facebook post, or enter this address into your search engine to access the nomination form:(https://webportalapp.com/webform/thankateacher) to nominate a K-12 Douglas County school employee who will be entered into a drawing to win a local business gift card. The nominee can be a teacher, classroom aid, custodian, counselor, principal, bus driver, nurse, cafeteria staff or other school personnel.

The first 30 nominations will receive a gift card. A total of fifty additional nominees will be selected June 4 and June 11.

Thank you to The Ford Family Foundation for sponsoring “Thank a Teacher/School Worker.”

#GratefulForYou

post_text: P-EBT can help you feed your family while schools are closed. If you already get SNAP or free school meals, you’ll get the benefits automatically. If you weren’t getting help before the pandemic but feel you may now qualify, apply online for free school meals at www.ode.state.or.us/apps/frlapp and apply for SNAP at https://govstatus.egov.com/or-dhs-benefits. If you qualify for either program, you’ll also get Pandemic-EBT!

post_text:
Did you know that Oregon is giving grocery money to families while school is closed? All families who are eligible for free or reduced price school meals will soon get funds on an Oregon Trail EBT card. Immigration status does not matter for Pandemic EBT.

If you already get SNAP or free school meals, you’ll get the benefits automatically.

Don’t miss out. If you weren’t getting help before the pandemic, apply online for free school meals at www.ode.state.or.us/apps/frlapp. Apply for SNAP at https://govstatus.egov.com/or-dhs-benefits. If you qualify for either program, you’ll also get Pandemic-EBT!

post_text:
Monday Night Lights @ SUHS

In honor of high school seniors across the state, high schools are turning on their football stadium lights from 8:00 pm to 8:20 pm. As some may know, 8:20 pm is 20-20 military time. South Umpqua High School will be participating in this event every Monday evening through the end of the school year.

This is not a gathering event, but a symbolic way for us to show our support for our seniors, families, and community.

Go Lancers!

post_text:
Next week, South Umpqua School District will host three community listening sessions to receive feedback about the district and how future funding from the Student Success Act should be used.

The meetings will be open to students, families and community members.

The Student Success Act marks a turning point for education in Oregon. When fully implemented, our state will see an additional $1 billion investment in schools each year.

For more information on the community listening sessions, call the district office at 541-863-3115.
